+## Why Not All Workflows Were Removed
+
+### Active Automation Discovery
+
+After checking workflow run history, I discovered that several agent automation workflows are actively in use:
+
+- `oc-issue-solver.yml`: Currently in_progress (as of 2026-01-22)
+- `oc-maintainer.yml`: Last run 2026-01-22T04:07:18Z (today)
+- `oc-pr-handler.yml`: Last run 2026-01-22T21:22:05Z (today)
+- `workflow-monitor.yml`: Actively running every 30 minutes
+
+Removing these active workflows would:
+1. **Disrupt ongoing automation** - Agents would lose ability to automatically solve issues, maintain repository, and handle PRs
+2. **Break current project workflows** - The project appears to rely on these automated agents
+3. **Cause immediate operational issues** - No guarantee that new workflows would replace agent functionality
+
+### Recommended Approach (For Maintainers)
+
+Instead of removing active agent automation, I recommend:
+
+#### Phase 1: Add Traditional CI/CD ✅ (DONE)
+- [x] Created `ci.yml` for automated testing and quality checks
+- [x] Created `security.yml` for security scanning
+- These provide proper CI/CD that was previously missing
+
+#### Phase 2: Analyze Agent Automation Needs
+- Document what each agent workflow actually does
+- Identify which agent workflows are essential vs redundant
+- Test if agents can be consolidated without losing functionality
+- Get consensus from maintainers on agent workflow strategy
+
+#### Phase 3: Consolidate Agent Workflows (If Needed)
+- Merge overlapping agent workflows (e.g., `oc-maintainer.yml` and `oc-problem-finder.yml`)
+- Reduce excessive permissions (`id-token: write`, `packages: write`, `pages: write`, `security-events: write`, `deployments: write`)
+- Remove `--admin` bypass flags (addressed separately in issue #629)
+- Add human approval requirements for sensitive operations
+
+#### Phase 4: Remove Redundant Workflows
+- Only remove workflows that are confirmed unused or duplicated
+- Disable first, monitor for 1 week, then delete
+- Update documentation
+
